   579ÔåÆ## Docs
   580ÔåÆ
   581ÔåÆDotenv exposes four functions:
   582ÔåÆ
   583ÔåÆ* `config`
   584ÔåÆ* `parse`
   585ÔåÆ* `populate`
   586ÔåÆ
   587ÔåÆ### Config
   588ÔåÆ
   589ÔåÆ`config` will read your `.env` file, parse the contents, assign it to
   590ÔåÆ[`process.env`](https://nodejs.org/docs/latest/api/process.html#process_process_env),
   591ÔåÆand return an Object with a `parsed` key containing the loaded content or an `error` key if it failed.
   592ÔåÆ
   593ÔåÆ```js
   594ÔåÆconst result = dotenv.config()
   595ÔåÆ
   596ÔåÆif (result.error) {
   597ÔåÆ  throw result.error
   598ÔåÆ}
   599ÔåÆ
      ÔåÆÔÇĞ
   605ÔåÆ#### Options
   606ÔåÆ
   607ÔåÆ##### path
   608ÔåÆ
   609ÔåÆDefault: `path.resolve(process.cwd(), '.env')`
   610ÔåÆ
   611ÔåÆSpecify a custom path if your file containing environment variables is located elsewhere.
   612ÔåÆ
   613ÔåÆ```js
   614ÔåÆrequire('dotenv').config({ path: '/custom/path/to/.env' })
   615ÔåÆ```
   616ÔåÆ
   617ÔåÆBy default, `config` will look for a file called .env in the current working directory.
   618ÔåÆ
   619ÔåÆPass in multiple files as an array, and they will be parsed in order and combined with `process.env` (or `option.processEnv`, if set). The first value set for a variable will win, unless the `options.override` flag is set, in which case the last value set will win.  If a value already exists in `process.env` and the `options.override` flag is NOT set, no changes will be made to that value. 
   620ÔåÆ
   621ÔåÆ```js  
   622ÔåÆrequire('dotenv').config({ path: ['.env.local', '.env'] })
   623ÔåÆ```
   624ÔåÆ
   625ÔåÆ##### quiet
   626ÔåÆ
   627ÔåÆDefault: `false`
   628ÔåÆ
   629ÔåÆSuppress runtime logging message.
   630ÔåÆ
   631ÔåÆ```js
   632ÔåÆ// index.js
   633ÔåÆrequire('dotenv').config({ quiet: false }) // change to true to suppress
   634ÔåÆconsole.log(`Hello ${process.env.HELLO}`)
   635ÔåÆ```
   636ÔåÆ
   637ÔåÆ```ini
      ÔåÆÔÇĞ
   648ÔåÆ##### encoding
   649ÔåÆ
   650ÔåÆDefault: `utf8`
   651ÔåÆ
   652ÔåÆSpecify the encoding of your file containing environment variables.
   653ÔåÆ
   654ÔåÆ```js
   655ÔåÆrequire('dotenv').config({ encoding: 'latin1' })
   656ÔåÆ```
   657ÔåÆ
   658ÔåÆ##### debug
   659ÔåÆ
   660ÔåÆDefault: `false`
   661ÔåÆ
   662ÔåÆTurn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being set as you expect.
   663ÔåÆ
   664ÔåÆ```js
   665ÔåÆrequire('dotenv').config({ debug: process.env.DEBUG })
   666ÔåÆ```
   667ÔåÆ
   668ÔåÆ##### override
   669ÔåÆ
   670ÔåÆDefault: `false`
   671ÔåÆ
   672ÔåÆOverride any environment variables that have already been set on your machine with values from your .env file(s). If multiple files have been provided in `option.path` the override will also be used as each file is combined with the next. Without `override` being set, the first value wins. With `override` set the last value wins. 
   673ÔåÆ
   674ÔåÆ```js
   675ÔåÆrequire('dotenv').config({ override: true })
   676ÔåÆ```
   677ÔåÆ
   678ÔåÆ##### processEnv
   679ÔåÆ
   680ÔåÆDefault: `process.env`
   681ÔåÆ
   682ÔåÆSpecify an object to write your environment variables to. Defaults to `process.env` environment variables.
   683ÔåÆ
   684ÔåÆ```js
   685ÔåÆconst myObject = {}
   686ÔåÆrequire('dotenv').config({ processEnv: myObject })
   687ÔåÆ
   688ÔåÆconsole.log(myObject) // values from .env
   689ÔåÆconsole.log(process.env) // this was not changed or written to
   690ÔåÆ```
      ÔåÆÔÇĞ
   692ÔåÆ### Parse
   693ÔåÆ
   694ÔåÆThe engine which parses the contents of your file containing environment
   695ÔåÆvariables is available to use. It accepts a String or Buffer and will return
   696ÔåÆan Object with the parsed keys and values.
   697ÔåÆ
   698ÔåÆ```js
   699ÔåÆconst dotenv = require('dotenv')
   700ÔåÆconst buf = Buffer.from('BASIC=basic')
   701ÔåÆconst config = dotenv.parse(buf) // will return an object
   702ÔåÆconsole.log(typeof config, config) // object { BASIC : 'basic' }
   703ÔåÆ```
   704ÔåÆ
   705ÔåÆ#### Options
   706ÔåÆ
   707ÔåÆ##### debug
   708ÔåÆ
   709ÔåÆDefault: `false`
   710ÔåÆ
   711ÔåÆTurn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being set as you expect.
   712ÔåÆ
   713ÔåÆ```js
   714ÔåÆconst dotenv = require('dotenv')
   715ÔåÆconst buf = Buffer.from('hello world')
   716ÔåÆconst opt = { debug: true }
   717ÔåÆconst config = dotenv.parse(buf, opt)
   718ÔåÆ// expect a debug message because the buffer is not in KEY=VAL form
   719ÔåÆ```
   720ÔåÆ
   721ÔåÆ### Populate
   722ÔåÆ
   723ÔåÆThe engine which populates the contents of your .env file to `process.env` is available for use. It accepts a target, a source, and options. This is useful for power users who want to supply their own objects.
   724ÔåÆ
   725ÔåÆFor example, customizing the source:
   726ÔåÆ
   727ÔåÆ```js
   728ÔåÆconst dotenv = require('dotenv')
   729ÔåÆconst parsed = { HELLO: 'world' }
   730ÔåÆ
   731ÔåÆdotenv.populate(process.env, parsed)
   732ÔåÆ
   733ÔåÆconsole.log(process.env.HELLO) // world
      ÔåÆÔÇĞ
   748ÔåÆ#### options
   749ÔåÆ
   750ÔåÆ##### Debug
   751ÔåÆ
   752ÔåÆDefault: `false`
   753ÔåÆ
   754ÔåÆTurn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being populated as you expect.
   755ÔåÆ
   756ÔåÆ##### override
   757ÔåÆ
   758ÔåÆDefault: `false`
   759ÔåÆ
   760ÔåÆOverride any environment variables that have already been set.
   761ÔåÆ
   762ÔåÆ&nbsp;
